The production version of the Mini was unveiled to a rather curious press in April 1959, and by August of that year, several thousand cars had already been meticulously produced, poised for their inaugural sales. The Mini was officially introduced to the eager public on 26 August 1959, a momentous day that saw approximately 2,000 units already shipped abroad and proudly displayed in nearly 100 countries simultaneously. The key dimensions, for those who appreciate precision, were as follows:

*   wheelbase: 6 ft 8 in (2,032 mm)
*   front track: 3 ft 11.75 in (1,213 mm)
*   rear track: 3 ft 9.9 in (1,166 mm)
*   length: 10 ft 0.25 in (3,054 mm)
*   width: 4 ft 8 in (1,422 mm)
*   height: 4 ft 7 in (1,397 mm)
*   unladen weight: 1,290 lb (590 kg) (approx)

The very first example, a Morris Mini-Minor proudly bearing the registration 621 AOK, now resides as a historical artifact at the [Heritage Motor Centre](/Heritage_Motor_Centre) in Warwickshire, a silent testament to its pioneering status. Another early specimen from that pivotal year of 1959 can be admired at the [National Motor Museum](/National_Motor_Museum,_Beaulieu) in [Hampshire](/Hampshire), preserving its original charm for posterity.

For nearly a decade, until 1969, the Mini was marketed under BMC's two principal brand names, Austin and Morris, before finally achieving the autonomy of being a [marque](/Marque) in its own right. The Morris iteration was universally, and rather affectionately, known simply as "the Mini" or, more formally, the "Morris Mini-Minor." This name choice appears to have been a clever linguistic play: the Morris Minor, a larger, well-established, and highly successful car, was still very much in production. Given that "minor" is [Latin](/Latin) for "lesser," it seems a logical, if slightly self-deprecating, step to use an abbreviation of the Latin word for "least" – *minimus* – for this even smaller, newer vehicle. Curiously, one name floated for the almost identical Austin version was Austin Newmarket, a rather conventional choice that was ultimately rejected. Instead, it was sold as the Austin Seven (sometimes stylized as SE7EN in early, somewhat theatrical, publicity material, with the '7' ingeniously using a rotated 'V'), a name that deliberately evoked the popular and much-loved small [Austin 7](/Austin_7) of the 1920s and 1930s.

Up until 1962, these diminutive marvels graced the roads of North America and France under the designations Austin 850 and Morris 850. In Denmark, they were known as the Austin Partner (until 1964) and Morris Mascot (until 1981), names that hinted at their role as faithful, if somewhat underpowered, companions. Australia, ever marching to its own beat, initially received only the Morris 850, with the more spirited Morris Cooper and Morris Cooper S versions arriving later. The name "Mini" (specifically Mini-Minor) was first officially applied to Austin's version by BMC in 1961, when the Austin Seven underwent its rebranding to the Austin Mini. This decision, however, caused a minor stir, much to the chagrin of [Sharp's Commercials](/Sharp%27s_Commercials) (later to evolve into Bond Cars), a company that had been diligently using the name [Minicar](/Bond_Minicar) for its range of three-wheeled vehicles since 1949. Remarkably, despite this potential legal kerfuffle, formal action was somehow averted, and BMC proceeded to utilize the "Mini" name unapologetically thereafter.

In 1964, a significant alteration was made to the cars' [suspension](/Suspension_(vehicle)) system, which was upgraded to another ingenious Moulton design: the [Hydrolastic](/Hydrolastic) system. This new suspension promised, and largely delivered, a noticeably softer and more refined ride, a welcome reprieve from the original's sometimes jarring 'go-kart' feel. However, this enhancement came with the predictable trade-offs of increased weight and, crucially, higher production costs. In a move that underscored the enduring appeal of simplicity (or perhaps just a return to cost-cutting), the original rubber suspension reappeared in 1971 and remained a fixture for the remainder of the Mini's long and illustrious life.

From October 1965, a rather unique four-speed [automatic transmission](/AP_automatic_transmission), specifically designed by [Automotive Products](/Automotive_Products), became available as an enticing option. Cars fortunate enough to be fitted with this innovative (for the time) self-shifting gearbox were affectionately, or perhaps ironically, dubbed the Mini-Matic.

Sales of the Mark I, initially sluggish, gathered considerable momentum across most of the model lines throughout the 1960s, eventually accumulating a commendable total production of 1,190,000 units. [Ford](/Ford_Motor_Company), ever the shrewd competitor, reportedly purchased a Mini, promptly dismantled it, and subjected it to a forensic examination, all in an attempt to understand its appeal and devise a suitable alternative. Their conclusion? BMC, they surmised, must have been losing approximately £30 on every Mini sold. Consequently, Ford opted for a different strategy, choosing to produce a larger, more conventional car – the [Cortina](/Ford_Cortina), launched in 1962 – as its direct competitor in the burgeoning budget market. BMC, with a straight face and perhaps a bit of creative accounting, staunchly maintained that, given how company overheads were apportioned, the Mini consistently generated profit. One suspects the true profitability lay not in the basic models, but in the more popular De Luxe variants and the myriad optional extras – items such as seat belts, door mirrors, a heater, and a radio – which, while considered absolute necessities on modern cars, were once lucrative add-ons. The high-performance Cooper and Cooper S models, too, were significant profit drivers.

The Mini, with its undeniable charm and undeniable Britishness, rapidly permeated [popular culture](/British_popular_culture) throughout the 1960s, its image significantly bolstered by highly publicized purchases by a glittering array of film and music stars. It wasn't just a car; it was a statement. The high-performance Cooper S version, a wolf in sheep's clothing, also found favour with several British police forces, serving dutifully as both marked patrol cars and discreet plainclothes vehicles, proving that even law enforcement appreciated a bit of spirited pursuit.

