The Mark II Mini made its grand debut at the 1967 [British Motor Show](/British_Motor_Show), introducing a series of subtle yet significant updates. These included a tastefully redesigned grille, a more expansive rear window to improve visibility (a welcome, if overdue, addition), and a host of other minor cosmetic alterations that aimed to refresh its iconic silhouette without alienating its devoted fanbase. During its relatively brief production run, a commendable total of 429,000 Mark II Minis were produced, cementing its place in the model's lineage.

A diverse array of Mini variants were also manufactured in [Pamplona](/Pamplona), Spain, under the stewardship of the [Authi](/Authi) company, commencing in 1968. These Spanish-built Minis were predominantly marketed under the Morris brand. In 1969, a rather unusual fibreglass-bodied version of the Mini Mark II was specifically developed for British Leyland's Chilean subsidiary (British Leyland Automotores de Chile, S.A., which had originally been the independent assembler EMSSA). The intricate mould for this lightweight bodyshell was expertly crafted by the [Peel Engineering Company](/Peel_Engineering_Company), a name more commonly associated with microcars. Production of these distinctive fibreglass Minis began in 1970 and continued for a few years, allowing them to be readily identified by their conspicuous lack of body seams and, rather tellingly, their somewhat larger panel gaps. The Chilean market, it must be noted, was never particularly vast, and the [Arica](/Arica,_Chile) plant eventually ceased operations in 1974. The primary rationale behind the adoption of the fibreglass body was to enable Leyland to meet the notoriously stringent local sourcing requirements imposed by the Chilean government, which mandated an increase to an ambitious 70.22% local content by 1971. A desperate measure, perhaps, but one that allowed the Mini to continue its global conquest.

